text: If post-Soviet politics in Eastern Europe seems confusing it is because the USSR was not a "corrupted" or reconstructed Russian Empire, but (as Galkovsky said) a parody of the British state, which was also its real owner. What you have here is colonial or post-colonial politics.

Legally the USSR was a new entity that conquered Russia's territory and destroyed it as a state and RF is its legal continuation. It was never an actual sovereign state like Russia in the 19th century. What is left now is an abomination decomposing on the beach.

Level 60 Galkovsky universe figure: "Alexander Parvus". International spy who funneled money to Gorky, travelled freely through Europe. He came up with a lot of ideas attributed to Lenin, Trotsky, Stalin, e.g. he created the "permanent revolution" concept associated with Trotsky.

Muddy bio, moved a lot as a child, educated in elite institutions in spite of supposed poor background, multiple false passports, infinite money coming from him, typical international spy. One of his nicknames was "Molotov". All of politics is intrigue between professional spies.

Mother Alexandra has a weird thing in her book on angels where she mentions Satan in Arabic is etymologically related to "remoteness", "to be remote" and Satan and his angels are somehow "evolving" (I guess "devolving" is more apt) towards remoteness and eventually nothingness.

When God asks Satan where he had been in the Book of Job he responds that he has been roaming the earth and this shows his lack of belonging and becoming more remote. If closeness to God means becoming holy, evil means increasing the distance from God's light more and more.

"Evil is the most distant thing from God, so distant that the end will be to evolve into the remoter and more satanic, into the nothingness and darkness of the bottomless pit of despair."

In 2 Enoch the gloomy fallen angels from the "second Heaven" beg Enoch to pray for their salvation. Shows that thing Fr. Stephen de Young from Lord of Spirits podcast talked about how for repentance it's necessary to be mortal and have a body. If you're immortal you can't repent.

The only way dead people and even fallen angels (even though obviously none of us should ever attempt the second) can repent and find salvation is through the prayers of a living mortal person. 2 Enoch obviously not the most canonic but u can see the idea clearly in that episode.
